This paper studies the effect of veteran status on wage income among those who hold a bachelor's degree.  We have a total of $500,000$ observations from the IPUMS ACS, from 2010 to 2019. We include control variables for  age, disability rating, physical and cognitive difficulty, sex, degree field, occupation, whether they live in a metropolitan area, and survey year fixed effects. The specific question of interest is: \textit{What is the effect of veteran status on wage income among those who hold a bachelor's degree?}.   

This question matters because military service may affect later labor market outcomes in several ways. On one hand, veterans may gain skills, such as discipline, leadership, and even valuable technical work experience that improves wages in the civilian market. On the other hand, military service may interrupt career development or cause health limitations that reduce earnings or the ability to work certain jobs, which could reduce earnings. Understanding this relationship is relevant for evaluating the transition of veterans into the civilian market and labor outcomes. 

Estimating this effect is difficult because veteran status is not randomly assigned. Veterans may differ from non-veterans in ways that could also affect earnings, such as age, gender, geography, and labor market experience. These factors may confound the relationship between veteran status and wages, so the raw differences in average income cannot automatically be interpreted as causal effects. 

This report presents a preliminary descriptive analysis of the data set. The goal is to understand the main patterns in the data and identify potential confounding factors.
